As you can see, it’s a mess! We need to clean it up a little before we continue. 🧹

chat <- chat %>% 
  filter(!str_detect(text, "omitted")) %>% # Remove messages saying "Image omitted", "video omitted", etc
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>% # Separates each word into a row and makes them lowercase
  filter(!(word %in% c("gil", "henriques", "sötnos", "linnea", "sandell"))) %>% # remove usernames
  filter(!str_detect(word, "[0-9]")) %>%  # remove numbers
  filter(!str_detect(word, "'")) %>%  # remove contractions
  filter(!str_detect(word, "^[a-z]$")) %>% # remove single letters (doesn't work with accents)
  mutate(date = ymd(date))

Many common words are simply words that are used often, such as “you”, “the”, or “for”. Let’s get rid of some of these:

wordlist <- wordlist %>%

That’s already better, but what we really want is to compare each word to how commonly they are used in English. So, we will need a wordlist of English words and their relative frequencies. 📖

I downloaded a corpus of 4934 college student American English SMS text messages created by Daniel R. O’Day of the Cyber Security Lab at Purdue University.

corpus <- read_delim("texts.txt", "\t", escape_double = FALSE, trim_ws = TRUE) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, message_body) %>% # Separates each word into a row and makes them lowercase
  filter(!str_detect(word, "[0-9]"), class == 0) %>%  # remove numbers
  select(word) %>% 
  group_by(word) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  mutate(source = "corpus") %>% 
  filter(!word %in% stop_words[stop_words$lexicon == "snowball",]$word)

We will use a metric called TFIDF, when means “term frequency - inverse document frequency”, whose value is higher for words that are more common in the chat history, and lower for words that are very common in the English language corpus:

df %>% 
  bind_tf_idf(word, source, n) %>% 
  filter(source == "chat") %>% 
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>% 
  mutate(word = factor(word, levels = rev(unique(word)))) %>% 
  top_n(50) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(word, tf_idf)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "tf-idf") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_ipsum_rc(grid = "X") +
  ylab("TFIDF (Frequency of word compared to American English college student text messages)") +
  labs(title = "What words distinguish our chats\nfrom average English texts?") +
  scale_y_continuous(label = function(x) {ifelse(x == 0, "0", parse(text=gsub("[+]", "", gsub("e", " %*% 10^", scientific_format()(x)))))})

There is a lot of interesting stuff going on here! Themes that distinguish our messages include:

  • Friends, family, and pets (“Ailene”, “Eva”, “Newton”, “Leonard”, “Neo”, “Brooke”) 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦
  • Work (“BRC”, “Sally”, “TA”, “Marking”, “EDG”, “Matt”, “Seminar”, “Theory”) 📝
  • Food (“Bread”, “Vegan”, “Salad”, “Tasty”, “Fruit”) 🥑
  • Languages (“Jag”, “Swedish”, “Du”, “Portuguese”, “Är”, “Duolingo”, “Det”) 🇵🇹 🇸🇪

And of course, there are also love-y words like “honey”, “kisses”, “cute”, and “pie” (probably from “honey pie”). 😘

Sentiment analysis

Sentiment analysis tells us whether the messages we are sending are positive or negative. We can start by finding the most used “positive” 👍 and “negative” 👎 words:

bing_positive <- get_sentiments("bing") %>% 
  filter(sentiment == "positive")
bing_negative <- get_sentiments("bing") %>% 
  filter(sentiment == "negative")

positive_words <- wordlist %>% 
  uncount(n) %>% 
  inner_join(bing_positive) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(sentiment = "positive")

negative_words <- wordlist %>% 
  uncount(n) %>% 
  inner_join(bing_negative) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(sentiment = "negative")

bind_rows(positive_words, negative_words) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  mutate(word = factor(word, levels = rev(unique(word)))) %>% 
  top_n(50, n) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(word, n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "count") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_ipsum_rc(grid = "X") +
  ylab("Frequency of word in chat") +
  labs(title = "Frequency of 'positive' and 'negative' words") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("tomato", "steelblue"))

We can also study how the sentiment changes over time. 📈

timeline <- chat %>% 
  mutate(month = month(date), year = year(date)) %>% 
  filter(!word %in% stop_words[stop_words$lexicon == "snowball",]$word)

timeline <- timeline[!(timeline$word %>% str_detect("'")),] 
timeline <- timeline[!(timeline$word %>% str_detect("^[a-z]$")),]

timeline %>% 
  inner_join(bind_rows(bing_positive, bing_negative)) %>% 
  group_by(year, month, sentiment) %>% 
  summarize(n = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = sentiment, values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate(date = lubridate::parse_date_time(paste(month, year, sep = "/"), "mY")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = positive-negative)) + 
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_ipsum_rc(grid = "Y") +
  xlab("Date") + ylab("Sentiment (Positive - Negative)") +
  labs(title = "Every month, our chats are more positive than negative")

It is clear that we use more positive than negative words. But how positive? So far we have been using a ternary scale—each word is either positive, or negative, or neutral. But we can also use a sentiment scale that ranges from very negative to very positive. Then, we can study how the frequency of each word correlates with its sentiment:

afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn")

afinn_wordlist <- wordlist %>% 
  inner_join(afinn) %>% 
  mutate(label = if_else(log(n) > 5 | value %in% c(-4, 4, 5), word, ""))

afinn_wordlist %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log(n), y = as.factor(value), label = label)) +
  geom_density_ridges(fill = "steelblue", 
                      quantiles = 2, 
                      alpha = 0.6,
                      jittered_points = F,
                      point_alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_discrete(expand = c(0, 0)) +
  coord_cartesian(clip = "off") +
  theme_ipsum_rc() +
  geom_point(aes(alpha = if_else(label == "", 0.2, 1)),
                 color = if_else(afinn_wordlist$label == "", "black", "gold")) +
  geom_label_repel() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  xlab("Log frequency of word in chat") + ylab("Sentiment (Negative to Positive)") +
  labs(title = "Overall, we use positive words more often than negative words")

In the figure above, I highlighted very negative (-4), very positive (4-5), and very common (>5) words. Although the pattern is not super strong, words we use most frequently are often more positive.

“Positive” and “negative” is not all there is to sentiment. There are many different types of sentiments. The next figure identifies what kinds of sentiments are most common in our chats:

Correlations between words

Words don’t exist in a vaccuum. We can also focus on words that often appear together. Every pair of words is called a bigram.

chat_bigrams <- read_csv("_chat.txt", col_names = c("date", "text")) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>% 
  filter(!(word %in% c("gil", "henriques", "sötnos", "linnea", "sandell"))) %>% # remove usernames
  filter(!str_detect(word, "[0-9]")) %>%# remove numbers
  filter(!str_detect(word, "'")) %>%# remove contractions
  unnest_tokens(bigram, word, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>%  # make everything lowercase
  select(bigram)

bigrams_separated <- chat_bigrams %>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")

bigrams_filtered <- bigrams_separated %>%
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words[stop_words$lexicon == "snowball",]$word) %>%
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words[stop_words$lexicon == "snowball",]$word)

bigram_counts <- bigrams_filtered %>% 
  count(word1, word2, sort = TRUE)

⚠️ “Image omitted” appears a lot because I imported the WhatsApp history into a text file, so every image or photo we ever sent each other is replaced with this message. 🖼

The data above can be used to create an plot a network:

bigram_graph <- bigram_counts %>%

  theme_void()

Follow the arrows between the blue points and you can see most of our most common text messages!

Comparing Gil and Linnéa’s texts

Since we are together all the time, you would be excused for thinking that we are, in fact, the same person. 👫 But the truth is that we are actually different, and that means we write differently as well.

We can verify this by studying our WhatsApp texts by author.

Calculating the distance to the \(x=y\) line, we can identify the words that most distinguish me from you.

frequency <- frequency %>% 
  mutate(distance_to_xy = sqrt((log(Linnea) - log(Gil))^2 / 2))

frequency %>%

Clearly, our texts share many words in common, but some words appear more commonly in my writing (“Néa”, “Michael”, “lovely”, and a lot of Swedish text), whereas other words are more frequent in your texts (“Babe”, “Gil”, “brain”, “Barbara’s”).

A better way to quantify the words that are more likely to come from me or from you is using a log odds ratio:

word_ratios <- chat_by_person %>% 
  count(word, person) %>%
  filter(nchar(word) > 1) %>% 
  group_by(word) %>%
  filter(sum(n) >= 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  spread(person, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, list(~(. + 1) / (sum(.) + 1))) %>%
  mutate(logratio = log(Gil / Linnea)) %>%
  arrange(desc(logratio))

I hope you enjoyed this gift 💝 and that you have a wonderful Valentine’s. I love you!! 💖

heart_fun <- function(n) {
  t <- c(seq(0, 2 * pi, length.out = n), 0)
  
  out <- data.frame(
    x = c(16 * sin(t) ^ 3),
    y = 13 * cos(t) - 5 * cos(2 * t) - 2 * cos(3 * t) - cos(4 * t)
  )
  out <- as.matrix(out)
  out <- list(out)
  st_polygon(out)
}

circle_fun <- function(n) {
  t <- c(seq(0, 2 * pi, length.out = n), 0)
  
  out <- data.frame(
    x = sin(t),
    y = cos(t)
  )
  out <- as.matrix(out)
  out <- list(out)
  st_polygon(out)
}

circle_heart <- function(n, center_sf, outside_sf, outside_filter = "None", plotting_margin = 5, ...) {
  
  bound <- function(x, limit) {
    ifelse(x > limit, runif(1, limit / 4, limit), x)
  }
  
  range <- st_bbox(center_sf)
  points <- data.frame(x = runif(n, range[["xmin"]] - plotting_margin, 
                                    range[["xmax"]] + plotting_margin),
                       y = runif(n, range[["ymin"]] - plotting_margin, 
                                    range[["ymax"]] + plotting_margin)) %>% 
    sf::st_as_sf(coords = c(1, 2))
  
  if (outside_filter == "buffer") {
    points <- st_intersection(points, st_buffer(center_sf, plotting_margin))
  } 
  
  points <- points[!lengths(st_intersects(points, center_sf)), ]
  
  all_polygons <- map(points[[1]],
    ~ (outside_sf * bound(st_distance(center_sf, .x, by_element = TRUE), 4)) + .x) %>%
  st_sfc()
  
  plotting_data <- data.frame(all_polygons) %>%
  mutate(x = map_dbl(geometry, ~st_centroid(.x)[[1]]),
         y = map_dbl(geometry, ~st_centroid(.x)[[2]])) 
  
  plotting_data %>%
    ggplot() +
    geom_sf(..., mapping = aes(geometry = geometry)) +
    coord_sf(datum = NA) +
    theme_void()
}

circle_heart(300, heart_fun(100), circle_fun(100), color = NA) +
  aes(fill = sin(x / y), alpha = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  guides(color = "none", fill = "none", alpha = "none")

This analysis was done with lots of help from Julia Silge and David Robinson’s book, Text Mining with R. The code for the heart at the end was modified (well, basically stolen) from this blog post by Emil Hvitfeldt.
